    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-04-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-04-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="762"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d762">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Marshall Mission Files, Lot 54–D270:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Thomas B. McCabe</persName> to
                        Brigadier General <persName type="to">Bernhard A. Johnson</persName>, at
                        Shanghai</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-22">22 April
                            1946</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>85280. 1. Reference your 28530 April 15, we do not agree to abandonment of offset
                    principle in surplus sales as proposed by Dr. Soong nor to proposed sale at
                    price formula to be set later. Subject to views of General Marshall which you
                    should secure we believe sales should be continued as rapidly as possible at
                    firm dollar prices. Dollar amount Yuan debt for 1945 and estimate for 1946 not
                    yet determined. Moreover until final determination US policy re lendlease
                    settlement it is impossible to estimate proportion Yuan debt that will be
                    available as offset surplus property. Decision expected soon. Until then surplus
                    sales may be made on tentative credit basis up to $150,000,000 sales value with
                    reservation US right finally to settle any part thereof on offset rather than
                    credit terms.</p>
                <p>2. If after completion of $150,000,000 sales as authorized paragraph 1 further
                    credits are needed to enable additional surplus purchases by Chinese question
                    should be referred here for consideration.</p>
                <p>3. In order to bring Chinese sales in line with other comparable credit
                    transactions the credits should be for 30 years at 2 and ⅜th% interest.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
